But what is nation in the abstract? A rather remote entity, removed from everyday experience. But homeland, where you have been born and live and work, a place you belong to, thatâ€™s a different proposition altogether. Women know intuitively, and experientially, what it means to be displaced, to be rendered homeless.

They know, that should they be uprooted from the place they call home, the dislocation will be physical, yes, but also profoundly emotional and psychological. Repeated and egregious references to Partitionâ€™s â€œunfinished businessâ€ by proponents of the â€œblack lawâ€ resurrect long dormant fears of the kind of destitution and violence that wreaks havoc in very particular ways, on women. They know how their religious identity can be made to turn against them.

This is why their protest this time is not about religion, it is about safeguarding their citizenship. It is about where you belong. It is about how you belong, and about why you belong. You belong not only because you have been born in this country, but because you have laid claim to its foundational values, you have owned them. By embracing the flag and the Constitution, the women of Shaheen Bagh â€” and the tens of thousands of men and women, of all faiths, who have joined them â€” have imbued the notion of Mother India with new meaning.

